ncial pressures, self-doubt, and political weakness. Simmons then identifies policy solutions and pragmatic strategies that college access organizations can adopt to address these factors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAcademic achievementzUnited States. 0aCollege attendancexSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCounseling in higher educationzUnited States. 0aMentoring in educationzUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 0aPeople with social disabilitiesxEducation (Higher)zUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aSimmons Memorial Foundation, college, access, education, university, higher education, policy, Delaware, North Carolina.1 aHewitt, Damon T.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813592916?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813592916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813592916/original  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK